{"/service/ndnp/vnstcsc/batch_vnstcsc_canaan_ver01/data/sn84037526/00513681252/1949031801/0249.xml":{"full_text":"The St. Croix Avis\nMORE THAN\nA CENTURY\noLp\nEBT. 1844\nCHAMPION OF PUBLIC RIGHT .ANOD JUSTICE\nPrinted and published every day except Sundays holidays by\nBRODHURST SONS\nChristiansted, St. Croi Virgin Islands, U. S. A,\nTelephone No. 48 P. O. Box 333\nEditor Manager e i Canute A. Brodhurst\nCirculation Manager 3 Anna C. Brodhurst\nAsst. Business Manager v C. A. Rrodhurst, Jr.\nSubscription rates:\n75 per month; $8:50 per year; $9.00 per year, Foreign\nAdvp:tiligg rates on request\nEntered as Second Class matter, May 26, 1917 at the Post Office at\n~hristiansted, St. Croix; V. I, under the Act of March 3, 1897.\nVOL. 105\nHousing Boom Danger\nUnderscored by 111.0\nFive years ago, the average value of a new one-family\nhouse in the United States was $3,089. At the end of 1947,\nin the midst of a housing boom, the cost of building that\nsame house had more than doubled. z\nAt the same time, a similar\nhousing boom was going on all\nover the world. Statistics made\npublic here by the International\nLabor Organization (ILO) show\nthat cost have advanced.\nThose high cost figures, which\nreally reflect the trouble that\nmillions of ordinary citizens have\nin finding moderate-priced hous-'\ning, have brought forth a warn-\ning from ILO against a repetition\nof the housing boom -which\nbrought disastrous results after\nWorld War 1.\nIn a study of employment in\nstability in the world construc\ntion industries, now: being -con\nsidered by the second session of\nILO\u2019s Building Civil Engineering\nand Public Works Committee\nmeeting in Rome, ILO asserts that\none of the first aims of govern\nments should be to stablize the\nindustry which has fluctuated so\nextravagantly in the past.\nPointing out the necessity of\nstabilizing the construction in\ndustry, the report siresses the\nfollowing points:\nIn the United States alone 2,300,\n000 workers and their families de\npend -on the buvilding industry for\ntheir livelihood.\nIn 20 other countries, from five\nto 10 percent of the population\nare employed in construction. l\nSince no other industry soars\u2019\nmore quickly to boom heights dur\ning good times or falls more rapid\nly to slump depths when demand,\nslackens, it is tHe responsibility of\ngovernments, employers and work!\ners to ensure that the 1950\" s do\nnot repeat the economically and\nsocially disastrous events of the\n30's, which sprang directly from:\nFRIDAY, MARCH 18, 1949.\ne e e\nthe last post-war boom.\nThe ILO study urges that gov\nernments employers and unions\nconcentrate their combined efforts\nto reduce costs in the \u00a2onstruction\nindustries through stabilization of\noutput.\n1. Governments should continue\ncheap money policies and should\nseek to maintain low interest rates\nparticularly on mortgages.\n2. Public works reserves from\nwhich projects can be drawn ds\nneeded to offset fluctuations in\nprivate investment should be built\nMp.\n3. A high degree of lab\u00e9r mo\nbility is required.\n4. The present high demand for\nhousing should be used in order\nto berfec} planning for any future\ndecline.\n5. Governments might subsidize\ncertain types of private invest\nment and provide housing subsi\ndies to those whose income is con\nsideredto be inadequate,\n6. Output stability could be at\ntained in part if governments used\ntheir powers to condemn subst\u00e9dn\ndard dwelling and .to promote\nhouse-building.\n7. State or local government pro\ngrams should be coordinated with\nthose of national governments.\n8. If forecasts are to be made\nin time to start public works when\n'they are needed, improvements\nwill be necessary in statistical an\nalyses and collection. 2 4%\n\u201cNever was an industry in more\nurgent need of cost reduction than\nthe housing industry,\u201d the ILO re\nport states. \u201cAlrea ,\u2019l\u2018y in some coun\ntries a rotential housing boom is\n-tending to be choked off by the\nTHE ST CROIX AvViIS\nhigh rising level of costs. The\nother construction industries are\nin th\u00e9 same state.\n\u201cProbably the greatest single.\nicontribution, to a reorganization\u2019\nof construction costs will be made\nif the output of the\u00ae industries is\n'successfully stabilized. Then, for\nithe first time, it will become eco\nnomical to undertake large-scale\n'methods of preducticn invo\u2018lvingl\n}heavy pver\ufb01e_ad expenses and o\nreduce and eventually to abandon\n}monopolistic and restrictive prac\ntices.\ni \u201cMany interesting and signifi\ncant exp\u00e9fiments are being made,\nand should be encouraged both by\ngovernments and by the trades\nindustries concerned, with \u2018deve\nlopments' such as standardization\nof materials and \u201cof sections of\nhouses and the introduction of fac\ntory processes and asgsembly-line\ntechnique.\u201d\nSTRENGTH\n\nuNITY\nNo. 62\nTODAY'S THOUGHT\nA recession is a period in\nwhich you tighten your belt.!\nIn a depression you have nol\nbelt to tighten. and when yow\u2019\nhave no panis to hold up, its\na panic.\n\u2014Farm Implement News'\ne peicai e\nRR T R S PA s\nOFFICIAL BULLETIN N 0.19\n-of the\n'FOOD COMMISSION OF\nST.'CROIX, V. I\nPursuant to Section 4 of the\nOrdinance of October 27, 1919,\nto create a Commission to re\nbulate and control the prices\nof foodstuffs in the Municipa\nlity of St. Croix, Virgin Is\nlands, and for other purposes,\nit is hereby brotight to Public\nNotice that the following are\nthe approved selling prices on\nthe \u2018Commodity listed below,\nwithin the Municipality of St.\nCroix, Virgin Islands.\nCommodity Not to Exceed\nLobster \u201cFresh\u201d. 15\u00a2 per 1b\nLobster \u201cBailed\u201d. 17\u00a2 per 1b\nThe foregoing prices to be\neffective on and after March\n218 t 1949,\nFrederiksted, St. Croix, V. L.\nMarch 17, 1949.\nDARNLEY A. PETERSEN\nChairman\nFOR SALE\n1941 SEDAN\nNewly painted. excellent\nrunning condition will\nsa\u00e9rifice for quick sale\nCommunicate: Avis Office\nAVAILABLE POSITION\nThere is available a position\n{in the unclassified service of\nithe Municipality of St. Thomas\nand St. John as General Mana\nger of the St. Thomas Power\nAuthority, with salary of\n1'54,800 per: annum,\nThe person to. be appointed\nto this position will be assign\ned highly responsible work in\ndirecting and supervising the\nbusiness and technical affairs\nof the:Authority. He will also\nb\u00e9 responsible for the eonstruc\ntion, maintenance, and Opera\ntion of the muncipal electric\ntransmission and distribution:\nsystem on the island: bf St.\nThomas, Virgin Islahdsof the\nUnited States.\nDesirable qualifications in\n.clude practical knowledge \u00a9f\n}and experience in construction.\n\"'and operation of electric distri\nbution systems and graduation:\n\u2018from a recognized college or\ni university with major work in\nthe field of Electrical Engineer\ning.\nPersans interested in this\nposition should make applica\ntion in writing to the under\nsigned not later than March\n22, 1949. Al applications\nshouldcontain full information\nas to the applicant\u2019s qualifica.\ntions and should be accompa\nnied by references.\nOffice of the Government Sec.\nCharlotte Amalie\nSt. Thomas, Virgin Islands\nMarch 8, 1949.\nMorris F. de Castro\nGovernment Secretary\nFOR SALE\nOne CHEVROLET Car\n_ N 0.288\nin good running condition.-\nNew Spare Tire\n\u2018Price: $350.00\nAlso two New Radios\u2014\nmakes as follows:\n1 Silvertone $40.00\n1 General Motors 40.00\nFor further information call at\nDAM'S Liquor Store\n\u00a57& s g\nBarbel's Taxi Service\nCourteous Dependable _\n(Careful Driving)\nISIDRO BARBEL Manager\nPage 3","height":"15330","width":"10860"}}
